    <definition xml:id="definition-TI8infinityint">
        <p>For a function <m>f(x)</m> and a constant <m>c</m>, we let <m>\displaystyle \int_c^\infty f(x) dx</m> denote <me>\int_c^\infty f(x) dx=\lim_{a\to\infty}\left( \int_c^a f(x) dx\right).</me>  If this limit is a defined real number, then we say <m>\displaystyle \int_c^\infty f(x) dx</m> is <em>convergent</em>, otherwise, it is <em>divergent</em>.</p>
        <p>Similarly, <me>\int_{-\infty}^c f(x) dx=\lim_{a\to-\infty}\left( \int_a^c f(x) dx\right).</me></p>
    </definition>
